    <div class="AssessmentProblem.type">ShortAnswerResponse</div>
    <div class="AssessmentProblem.statement"><p>A chef is making pickles. He needs 15 gallons of vinegar. The store sells 2 gallons of vinegar for <span>$</span>3.00 and allows customers&#xA0;to buy any amount of vinegar.&#xA0;Decide whether each of the following ratios correctly represents&#xA0;the price of vinegar.</p>

<ol>
	<li>4 gallons to <span>$</span>3.00</li>
	<li>1 gallon to <span>$</span>1.50</li>
	<li>30 gallons to <span>$</span>45.00</li>
	<li>
<span>$</span>2.00 to 30 gallons</li>
	<li>
<span>$</span>1.00 to <span class="math math-repaired" data-png-file-id="781">\(\frac23\)</span> gallon<presentation-tag data-tag-title="1 INCH" data-tree-code="MS_pi" data-tree-node-id="243962" data-tree-ref-id="215" src="/presentation_tags/4.tag"></presentation-tag><presentation-tag data-tag-title="1 INCH" data-tree-code="Accel6_8" data-tree-node-id="260635" data-tree-ref-id="218" src="/presentation_tags/4.tag"></presentation-tag>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
    <div class="AssessmentProblem.solution"><ol>
	<li>No. (The ratio is not equivalent; 4 gallons of vinegar would cost <span>$</span>6).</li>
	<li>Yes. &#xA0;</li>
	<li>Yes.&#xA0;</li>
	<li>No. (The ratio is not equivalent; 2 gallons of vinegar&#xA0;cost <span>$</span>3, and&#xA0;<span>$</span>30 would buy 20 gallons).</li>
	<li>Yes.&#xA0;</li>
</ol>
</div>
